person.name: Alexander Betaev
person.title: software systems analyst/designer/engineer
person.description:
the I-section

I like to solve puzzles, learn about new things. Listening to music inspires me. I like art of different kinds; PC games are one of the kind.

I am passionate about making things right, and I believe that our humane aspiration to order is tightly related to the overall source of life. My way of thinking may seem erratic, I always try to think critically, rotate a subject in mind, see it from all the angles I am able to imagine.

few words about this page

As you will (or might have already) notice(d), I have been working in Grid Dynamics for a while. At some moment something turned upside down, and all the projects I have been asked to work on were not quite making sense to me.

So, after rejecting few projects and being in almost complete isolation from society for a while already, I have been notified that the company does not have any work for me and lets me go free. I could not have missed such an awesome offertunity. So I started to look for other ways to express myself in this world, get enough recognition to keep on my lonely living.

The idea emerged, and it appeared to be recursive in a sense, that I will create such a thing that shows how I create things.

This web page is such a thing, that demonstrates my creative abilities, but not everything is visible yet. And you are, obviously, still reading. As a gratitude for your attention, I want to tell two secrets.

The first is that if you make "idkfa" query to this webpage it will reveal friend-mode, allowing access to slightly deeper demonstration of myself.

As for the second: there is another query which provides some more control over the site.

the "WANT" part of the deal

What do I want? - The peace on planet Earth, my piece of planet Earth...

But... the existence of the latter eradicates chances for the former to exist: a property of any kind creates inequality. So...

... what do I really want?ü§î

"A (hu)man is made for happiness, like a bird for a flight."

~ Paradox, Vladimir Korolenko

But happiness has never been for trade and never can be. It's not a product, it can't be created; it's a state, one can achieve it.

Being conscious and self-aware is one part; being able to create useful things is another part. And these two are ingredients to the simple recipe of my happiness.

I want to create. And it's a huge benefit if whatever I create has meaning to me, because meaning drives me.

_________
Sincerly,
Alex

I was young, trees were big, we hanged a lotü•≥

I experimented a lot, studying a little. During this period, I have learned that the best learning is hands-on experience.

For some time I was on Slackware Linux writing custom boot scripts and for whatever reason making boot process interactive... that looked so cool back then, that I can completely customize how the system works.

Spent few years on Gentoo, building the whole system almost from scratch... Yeah, well, I managed to build Gnome 2 on Slackware before by using just provided documentation, so automated Gentoo builds were giving me awe, rather than anxiety. I remember building (emerging?) OpenOffice for like 2 days in a row on Core 2 Duo E6600 with somewhat 2 or 4 gigs of ram... That PC is still running Linux, by the way :)

By the end of my education I was steadily living on beer, ArchLinux with a complete lack of understanding of what that all was aboutü§Ø

My greatest achievement was a Snake game written in a weird mix of C and C++ (I was not that good of a code writer back then) with use of x86 assembly (to turn on VGA graphics mode) and direct memory access (to write into graphics memory). experience.title: Childhood

Dad assembled the first computer in my life in about 1988, in my life that has just begun on January 8, 1986. I remember playing some Lode Runner clone on it... and that's all that I remember about that device.

Later I had few ZX Spectrums, starting from 48Kb model with tape reader up to 128Kb reading 5" diskettes.

Somewhere around that time I started to query the reality of being for sense and purpose...

experience.title: Curriculum Vitae
experience.description:
Introduction

The last assignments I've been given in Grid Dynamics after almost a half of year of silence were to update my CV, pass some trainings and to evaluate the performance of one, I should say, pretty talented guy. The latter, sadly, I wasn't able to complete before our relationships with the company ended, but this story is not about it at all...

It is about the CV and my awkward surprise when I realized that the company, who's main business is to sell software engineers, does not have a tool to demonstrate such an awesome product. A shoemaker without shoes? More like a shoemaker without tools (or with wrong tools?..). Anyway, to the point: I was asked to update word document (okay, that was cloud word document, but stillü§¶üèª‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è)

This page is the product of 5 weeks of work which included:

  • analysis of the subject's domain

  • design of meaningful functionality related to that domain

  • development of an application (okay, web application, but stillüíÅüèª‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è)

This whole thing has the intention to demonstrate my skills.

The CV Application

NOTE: I recommend a dark theme to watch through the following pictures, otherwise some details may not be visible; I know it's a bug, but pictures' main purpose was for me to lean my thoughts on, so I just copied them with almost no modifications

Description

I have watched few videos on YouTube to complete my idea (inspired by the shoemaker company) with a functional picture:

The employer (structure of interest) consists of 3 actors which may presumably be on my way to employment.

NOTE: It's probably worth to mention that all behavioral entities on the pictures are rounded and all structural are squared. I use green color to mark the domain I operate with and have full control, red for the domain which states up the requirements and the blue one for the domain which I cannot affect directly, but it's still part of the whole thing.

The Domain Model

The domain diagram does not follow the global color notation: I had to show a bit deeper hierarchy and decided to use additional colors for that purpose:

I consider this model to be the core part of the whole application, and, for me, it opens paths to a lot of functional possibilities.

But I gave myself 6 weeks so there was not a lot of space for maneuvers. The functionality should've been narrowed to something feasible.

Here are the (formed) thoughts I have regarding this model:

  1. This picture describes some kind of a hierarchical document

  2. Such a document should consist of 2 main sections

    1. Personal (marked as "Person") - such section contains information about the person who is represented in the CV, like a business card you would give to someone, but is not part of the CV itself.
      The logic behind was that "curriculum vitae" translates as "the course of life" (from Latin) and person's business card does not fit such meaning

    2. CV itself - the description of a person's life, which consists of two parts:

      1. Experience - person's life experience, I guess, everyone would agree is the crucial part of any CV
        I decided to go a bit deeper and have hobbies as part of experience. I decided to make it invisible, to "filter out" those who aren't really interested.

      2. Profile: this section came out of an idea that for each job I may need to have different skills which stand out, therefore I would need to adjust my CV.
        This part was not included into the first release. I have added the basic functionality to the current one.

Metadata is what binds profile and experience together. Currently I use metrics based on tags.

The System Architecture

It's very simple diagram which identifies top-level structure of the whole system. Its main goal is to show how actors are integrated into the system.

How is it supposed to work?

I generally use sequence diagrams to answer such questions. Here's the one that visualizes the CV App's process:

By coincidence, this picture contains the second secret, which reveals the rest of the functionality.

One of the ideas behind the public CV was to hide some data I did not want to expose to everyone. Also I wanted to be able to create versions compatible with Applicant Tracking Systems, give human actors convenience to get fully featured CV without a hassle and make it personalizable... at least a little bit :)

Deeper dive

These diagrams were created after the first milestone was released.

I always start from use cases:

The exported blue part corresponds to the parts of same color on the main model. I had to limit such data because wanted it to be encodable with QR code for convenience.

At some point I came up with the following structure:

There are some more thoughts and diagrams, but they are too raw.

The afterword

What you see is just a sketch of an idea. It may change a lot during the creative process. And not a single part of such process can either be completely avoided or fully delegated. To build an implementation of an idea, the whole concept of it needs to become sensible through all possible channels of perception.

I worked a lot with very abstract "ideas", those which are not completely sensible. Often I discovered that such "idea" is not the best way to achieve its goal (pinching), or that it do not make any sense in full picture view (tearing). And it is a part of the process too.

Abstraction is a tool to deal with complexity, but as any tool it may be used wrong. And, instead of zooming in or out, some pinching or even tearing happens and a canvas of an idea changes in an unpredictable way.

I use UML to keep tearing at minimum. It does not help to avoid pinching, but makes it easier to notice.

I hope, you had a joyful experience exploring this little idea of mine.

___________
Alexander

Deno.description:
this is... Deno... that comes from Node... well it's typescript/javascript runtime which is working on Google's v8... but that's not the point.

the point is, that the convenience of the language runtime was significantly improved with making it more like Go lang toolset is designed -- a single kill'em'all executable to shoot all legs at once without any external dependencies, which, by the way, can be imported as simple as

```typescript
import { assertEquals } from "https://deno.land/std@0.179.0/testing/asserts.ts";
```

Java.description:
The language i spoke for the longest part of my career. It's like Go nowadays, clumsy, corny, but used by everyone who writes backend.

I stopped diving into details of what's going on in Java since Java8. The last time I developed something (Quarkus that was) for Java 11 or 13... But recently I've seen some article about Java 20-something, so... I guess we are slowly getting yet another Kotlin hereü¶Ü

ytt.description:
If expressed in math ratio terms, ytt to YAML is same as XSLT for XML...

If some part of an audience of this humble CV have missed that wonderful age of W3C standards emerged on the edge of 2000's, the other words to explain ytt would be: declarative programming language (not Turing-complete!) to manipulate structure of YAML documents.

Areas of application, considering ubiquity of YAML in modern tooling configurations (K8S, Concourse CI, serverless.com, AWS CloudFormation, Spring Boot, Spring Cloud, ...), are pretty straight forward.

AWS Lambda.description: AWS Lambda is a service which provides functional integration pattern which is able to glue a lot of  other AWS services together into a complex event driven system.

AWS API Gateway.description:
it's an AWS way to define API's

i still cannot make sense out of a lot of design decisions AWS guys made while creating this ugly monster, but, apparently, they are not rushing to rethink this clumsiness.

AWS DynamoDB.description:
Column base database, the ancestor of Cassandra.

Has it's specifics and the most interesting, probably, is how much will service using it will cost and how to reduce that cost.

serverless.com.description:
opinionated tool set to define simplified cloudformation stacks reduced to pretty narrow subset of "micro services", which in opinion of authors are always lambdas bound to API Gateways.

AWS SAM is more adequate view from the AWS point, and my professional recommendation would be to avoid using this particular tool, even if you already do.

it's kinda abstraction for sake of abstraction without any particular benefits.

Spring Boot.description: The toolkit from Spring Framework which to create executable .jars. All the blows and whistles of Spring IOC included into the box... which is generally pretty big.

Spring Cloud.description:
or some call it Netflix OSS, where the branding takes its part

Spring Cloud is all-in-one collection of standards and implementations to build on-prem cloud:

  • discovery

  • configuration

  • load balancing

  • circuit breakers

  • tracers

  • and many more... working almost out of the box on the infrastructure of your choice.

i have even taken security pattern implemented in spring-config-server to create something similar, but cloud-native, within AWS

Hazelcast.description:
In-memory data grid, which Hazelcast was at that point, is a computing service which operates with data held in-memory, obviously.

Unfortunately the only use case for Hazelcast in the system i worked on was to be a cache between service and Cassandra... which is in it's own way a cache. So I was quite confused about all the decisions made.

At some point I have even created a computing plugin for the system, that plugin was a Hazelcast based service which was operating with Hazelcast data and computing some values based on business logic. probably that was the one and only occasion when Hazelcast was used not as just cache on that project.

XML.description:
eXtensible Markup Language, they say... year, cumbersome as well :)

knowledge of XSD included

AWS S3.description: S3 is cloud storage service, probably the most popular one.

Typescript.description: One of the most exiting programming tools of the past decade. I very like this tool, as much as i used to hate javascript/ecmascript for it's incompleteness, this is the part which it was missing all the way and now it's here.

Concourse CI.description:
very simple, yet powerful continuous integration system:

* if you are still using Jenkins, please don't. this is the proper way out ;)
* if you want to build CI on prem, this is a good way to go

`YAML` configuration, awesome simplicity combined with versatility, support for a lot of integrations and beautiful icons :)

FreeSwitch.description:
this is a very legacy piece of s..technology, with decades of functioning in different enterprises and serving phone calls over multilines to directors and clerks.

it has some specifics which produce requirements to network setup, the way it is encapsulated for deployment and the way such deployment can be scalable.

i had quite a few moments with this software, and would recommend to avoid using it except if you don't have some specific dependencies on very few features OpenSIPs cannot provide.

Google Dialogflow.description:
if i remember correctly, this was a separate product, later acquisited by Google.

anyhow, it's pretty interesting piece of software which allows to design dialogues between machine and -other machine- human. basically it provides a way to define the dialog structure (looks like graph, feels like flow :)) and integration points when certain points were reached.

it has notion of context, which allows to define really human-like interactions and reduce robot dumbness to minimum...

i don't really like those poorü§ñ IVRs which ask you ten times to say social security and then fallback to legacy tone input. but IVRs designed with Dialogflow can be really... humane?

Kubernetes.description:
convenient and versatile abstraction over infrastructure.

i did not dive deep into details of k8s itself, i did not need to, but i had an experience of making a pocket version of CI which:
* has a self-deployment capability by creating k3s (k8s implementation) cluster
* bundled with deployment framework to support deployments to an arbitrary k8s cluster

all built in one box setup for security and minimal human interaction

Quarkus.description:
yet another attempt to make something as successful as Spring, yet constrained with standards of new (but already past) era like CDI, JAX-RS, JPA&JTA.

Quarkus aims to be fast, yet versatile.

Quarkus to Spring is like Ruby to Python.

Yet another fight of TIOOWTDI vs TIMTOWTDI...

Isn't it obvious that Javascript always wins?..

zeroconf.description:
zeroconf is a bundle of protocols to establish ad-hoc service networks.

Primary use was intended for home networks, where you can connect to WI-FI and be able to print on the printer which is within the same network (or is connected to a computer withing the same network), stream audio, turn off iron and tweak a/c.

It turns out to be quite a good solution for enterprises who do not want a mess with printers, but want all that plun'n'pray stuff happening automagically.

GCP Compute.description:
Compute is very convenient and versatile product of Google Cloud Platform.

i really liked working with it, was able to easily setup blue/green for quite complex deployment of telephony stack

i can compare it to AWS Compute which is not so intuitive and does not provide such convenience, while being functionally on the same level.

GCP Datastore.description:
i had a slight touch of it. 

it's a kind of non structured NoSQL document database which holds JSON's and allows to build indices agains them.

at the time i was trying to make use of it, there was no way to subscribe Cloud Function to a DB even. that feature was going to be introduced with the later version

bash.description: well... i am still sometimes confused how arrays like ${@} are substituted when you pass them downstream, and i will definitely google (or should i say chatgpt instead nowadays?) how to write a hook on a SIGTERM to clean up the mess ;)

GCP VPC networks.description: Since i had to work with infrastructure on the IVR project at Home Depot, i could not pass by the GCP Networking. it was not a deep dive, but i have enjoyed their flat firewalls spread across VPCs and convenience provided by both CLI and cloud console to configure network topologies.

Docker.description:
one of the first containerization products widely spread on the market.

it has it's flaws and brought a lot of good stuff to modern containerization like Dockerfiles, docker-compose being something pre-k8s, container registries

MIP.description:
MIP, mixed integer programming, is the way to define an optimization problem.

It's generally represented as a system of equations and inequalities which define constraints and a goal which is to either minimize or maximize value of one of variables from those equations without going out of boundary.

In software engineering terms MIP is a framework to define and solve optimization problems.

OR-Tools.description:
Provided by Google engineers, this is a collection of optimization algorithms with convenient to use bindings for different languages.

I used Java bindings, but there are bindings for Python as well as for C++ and .Net

React.description:
one of the most popular web UI frameworks for quite a while.

attempts like VueJS failed to replace it, but minimalistic approaches like Preact beat React almost in anything, so today i would go with Preact instead.

nevertheless it is really important to note that the most attractive feature of React and Preact is JSX, which is basically Javascript syntactic extension to embed HTML-like code into Javascript (and Typescript). if it is the only feature you are looking for, i strongly encourage you to look at SolidJS as the most wonderful implementation of JSX i have ever seen.

this CV is built on SolidJS and i would never have chosen any Svelte, Vue or (P)React over it.

Semantic UI.description:
it's the first UI component library i picked to create simplistic UIs to provide an access to service.

the development i made using this framework was for internal use

ParcelJS.description:
zero-configuration javascript bundler for browser and node.

i like such tools which do not require me to dig through documentation to make them work. it just works!

Apache Cassandra.description:
column based database optimized for high volumes of data write and read with quite impressive consistency.

it is really great product when you use it for it's strengths and not trying to create a relational database out of it because you were just told to do so by some inadequate guy who somehow got his shiny "architect" badge.

i had some experience using Cassandra in DSE (DataStax Enterprise) package which included Spark and SOLR. and that was very powerful bundle to build scalable data system of you dream.

ELK Stack.description:
i can proudly say that i have used full ELK stack to do visualization of order sourcing system (based on US ZIP codes only, but still).

all three components were working in order to demonstrate how order will be delivered from several locations to one on beautiful and slow Kibana.

Machine Learning.description:
This is where machines become... more intelligent :)

I have an intuition, but have not had a chance to apply it in practice.

Algorithms.description:
Algorithms is inevitable part of our everyday lives, not only software engineering. With such an erratic mind I am no way a good mathematician, but algorithms is not only a math.

From the most basic like divide and conquer and branch and bound to the different types of heuristic searches over huge spaces of options and machine learning which is not always considered as algorithm (but what is it then?)... There is so much about algorithms. No single human can fit all that into their head (without cybernetic extensionsü§ñ)

When I solve a problem which requires knowledge of an algorithm, I generally try to build an intuition around it. It helps a lot to step aside and allow subconsciousness do its part in the solution. I am really bad at coding interviews, and if I solve a problem in a form of working code, it will generally mean that I had met such or somewhat-alike problem earlier (not necessarily solved though). And that's how I think.

Data Structures.description:
Data structures, those abstract entities which generally serve carcases for algorithms as bones for our bodies.

From something simple like a dense array and linked lists to tensors and graphs and sets smoking asideüö≠

Again as with algorithms: I don't know it all, but know some I came across.

Spring Core.description: the core part of Spring framework, beans, XML and annotation processors, ...

Apache Spark.description:
(Big)Data processing engine. Awesome piece of tech allowing to distribute computation over a large cluster of nodes.

Spark provides several different APIs for user's convenience.

I personally worked with low-level RDDs and higher level Dataframes.

Scala.description:
It's ugly as C++ and much more functional. Nah, I like C++ much better!

I did not have lot of experience with Scala. It was more like few simple lines. I know it's pretty powerful, but all my attempts were strongly deflected to ∆õaskell. I just do not like Scala¬Ø\_(„ÉÑ)_/¬Ø

ATG.description:
one of those things i wish i never knew...

But at that time I was pretty excited to the point where I was able to tear it apart, run on in-memory database, create maven plugin with JUnit integration and other blows and whistles... oh, how much energy was in that pointless effort!!!üí©üò´

Jenkins.description: This one had not ever needed to be renamed from Hudson. Hudson itself should be the last evolutionary step to extinction, but somehow both still thrive and exist. Oh, world...

Maven.description:
It's quite old, yet cozy java build tool.

Cumbersome XMLs act like woolen plaid, you dive in and never want to get outü•¥

Gradle.description: Yet another Java build tool. Not so cozy as Maven, but so versatile in its monstrosity that contains Turing-complete Groovy script which allows you to go out of the box and make things, create things, break things and much-much more!

hybris.description: Pretty versatile eCommerce platform, contains accelerators to build stores of different kinds.

MySQL.description: very old yet still quite popular relational database

IBM WebSphere Message Broker.description: very versatile integration engine capable to work with systems of all kinds and all times. clumsy as much as versatile, though

EJB3.description: really, what can be interesting about this? especially when world market is crushing

SOAP.description:
it's not so soapy when you use it.

pretty rigid standard based on XML. using JMS transport (even? especially?) in those times was additional pain in the butt, but i made it work somehow.

JMS.description: API which is included into JavaEE API bundle

JPA.description: yet another API from JavaEE bundle

C++.description:
Oh, I like this one. I don't have a lot of experience, but it was one of those which gave me an understanding of computer linguistics.

It was not only C++, but also a little bit C, which I was able to translate into x86 assembler. But C++ added some fun stuff like virtual function lookup tables, i.e. RTTI (runtime type information - it's kinda C++'s implementation of reflection, but not quite).

All those wonderful segfaults of my beginnings wonderfully vanished with Java-pillüíä

Embarcadero C++ Builder.description: WYSIWYG IDE for C++ in Windows

AWK.description:
Turing-complete programming language aimed on text processing.

I always preferred it to perl.

Turing-completeness does not imply general purpose ;)

VMWare virtualization.description: I used it to test my automation scripts and reduce development cycle while working in SPb Metro.

MS SQL.description: SQL from Microsoft until it all have not exploded into clouds.

Math.description:
I am okay with linear algebra and calculus, but I didn't happen to meet it a lot in my career, so some time would be needed for me to get along ¬Ø\_(„ÉÑ)_/¬Ø

I enjoy worlds where imagination can be applied, and math is an awesome tool to embed rigid structures into such worlds, to build something beautiful.

TFS.description: Bureaucratic monster created in bowels of another bureaucratic monsterüëæ

SolidJS.description:
This is the best DOM manipulation framework with JSX support I know.

Of course, it's just my opinion, but I have tried vue, react, preact, I carefully walked angular as much far around as possible, I used bare HTML with JS and CSS... And I find SolidJS the best way to create web applications, something awesome like Haskell, but available as a pizza!

If you are UI developer and have never tried SolidJS, give it a chance. It's worth it.

js.description: Nice visualization library, I think the most popular or one of the most, at least. I am not ready to use plotly or d3 :) d3, though, is one of those things I would like to put my hands on.

Vite.description: Plug and play frontend tooling for node projects.

Julia.description:
I used it to do data analysis mostly. Parsing CSVs and producing graphs.

No linear algebra here; I just looked through the course on Coursera.

I remember I was quite impressed by the language type system. It's like in Typescript, but dynamically typed... or was it also statically typed... Though those memories are already fuzzy, the point is, I did not use it a lot.

com.description:
Highly opinionated cloud model to run microservice architectures, designed to abstract everything from cloud-native configurations into some kind of generic yaml which never gets generic.

I have used it in couple with AWS and to produce something more-or-less livable it is always required to add native code within that yaml which makes that yaml quite useless for solving the original goal.

I had no chance to change minds of those who decided to use this strange piece of software as core part of their system.

Groovy.description:
They have invented groovy to script in Jenkins, right?.. or maybe not only in Jenkins. I used it to script some stuff in Jenkinsfiles and .gradle files.

It's like Java, but more "scripty", like in java-scripty, but only if you take few deep breaths while saying the dash sign.

Spring Integration.description:
Integration framework based on Spring XMLs.

You define flows in the most cumbersome XML format I could not ever imagined with almost zero convenience if you do have special IDE for that. And you definitely might not have one because such IDE requires financial investments.

It only me or it is making an impression that such Java library like spring-integration exist only to justify price of the IDE required to conveniently use them?

I am talking about IntelliJ IDEA from JetBrains, which community version does not give Spring support. And while there exists (and existed at the time of me using this wonderful library) open source Eclipse IDE, it had it's own flaws, so big, that not everyone would prefer it to text editor which does not crash at all.

FFT.description:
The Fast Fourier transform.

I don't know the math behind it, but I understand its application in digital signal processing (DSP). This algorithm is analogue data analysis algorithm. In DSP it, given a wave, can extract frequencies of which such wave is composed.

Considering that the whole world is wavy (especially lately) probably we should compute FFT a bit more often to understand what's going onüåä

Subversion.description:
It's interesting whether anyone remembers it's "best practices" in centralized times.

I don't follow the topic at all, but, I think, I've heard that they addresses few of the issues. Not sure if we need anything but Git nowadays, but the migration of mindset from SVN to GIT was pretty uncomfortable, almost like, why did they do it this way? Therefor I was always for mercurial, which was more SVN-like in terms of interface.

Anyway, today I use only Git and not sure if there's any other version control system needed in this world.

git.description:
It has its flaws, but mostly it's okay.

Don't think there should be any alternative any time soon, except for maybe very specialized something that can be created out of git itself.

Pico CSS.description: Neat minimalistic CSS framework. I took it as base for this project with almost no modifications.

OpenSIPS.description: I slightly touched it. Mostly dealt with FreeSwitch.

XSLT.description: Extremely powerful stuff. Don't come near. It'll blow you mind and wrap it over the globeü§Ø

Oracle DB.description: The Cthulhu of all the relational databasesüêô

IBM DB2.description:
An "ultimate" version of a relational database from IBM, I guess...

With this one I have the least experience.

BNB.description:
This no not what you are thinking !(üõèÔ∏èüç≤)

It's branch and bound, the tree walking technique to solve algorithmic problems. There are several building blocks for this algorithm: a tree with branches and boundaries to operate within. Though the developer is responsible for creating such tree, and the was they create it may result in different performance.

I used BNB to create an optimization algorithm for order sourcing. Later I found OR-Tools and formulated same task in MIP terms.

OR-Tools were generally better.

LCS.description:
Longest Common Sub-sequence

This is an algorithm a software developer may need to build a diff. It allows to distinct between similar and different chunks of data, whether they are lines within a text or letters within a line.

It is applicable to ordered data structures like text, string or any other form of ordered list. But when you deal with sets or unordered arrays (arrays in which order does not matter), you'll need other algorithms... much more simple, though
